comment_data.body: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/15430 looks related. Should this also be moved to flutter/flutter-intellij?
@zoechi: I think flutter/flutter#15430  is more on the flutter tools side so probably belongs where it is.

I tried following "Creating a new project from existing source code" from the Flutter site (https://flutter.dev/docs/development/tools/android-studio) but AS basically just overwrote my project. Tried importing it but I'm unable to run it. Run button is disabled.

Is it not straightforward to import existing Flutter projects in AS?

> I tried following "Creating a new project from existing source code" from the Flutter site (https://flutter.dev/docs/development/tools/android-studio) but AS basically just overwrote my project. Tried importing it but I'm unable to run it. Run button is disabled.
> 
> Is it not straightforward to import existing Flutter projects in AS?

Can confirm this still happens in Android Studio 3.5.3 for Windows

after bothered by this for months... I finally found this in doc

it says: 
Important: Do not use the New > Project from existing sources option for Flutter projects
Instead, choose "Start a new Flutter project", and Under Project location enter, or browse to, the directory holding your existing Flutter source code files.
Click Finish.

https://flutter.dev/docs/development/tools/android-studio#creating-a-new-project-from-existing-source-code

Still an issue in Android Studio 4.0.2 for Windows.  A large number of developers are using VS Code so this problem is pretty major and very annoying.  It seems like I should be able to import the project and point AS to the pubspec.yaml.

milestone.description: Work triaged but not yet planned for a specific release.
